 duped by a charismatic leader nor working class anti-heroes, this book introduces EDL activists as individuals with real lives whose diverse trajectories in and out of activism are embedded in personal life stories.The book will be of value to those researching or studying in the disciplines of sociology, political science and anthropology as well as those with an interest in contemporary political issues and the populist and radical right.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnology. Social and cultural anthropology. 0aSociology (General). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aEnglish Defence League.  aEthnography.  aFar right organisations.  aIslamophobia.  aPolitical activism.  aPopulist radical right movements.  aSocial movements.1 aPilkington, Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526114013zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526114013zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526114013/original  a978-3-11-128282-4 Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA